# Git 

## Semantic Commit Messages
- feat: (new feature for the user, not a new feature for build script)
- fix: (bug fix for the user, not a fix to a build script)
- docs: (changes to the documentation)
- style: (formatting, missing semi colons, etc; no production code change)
- refactor: (refactoring production code, eg. renaming a variable)
- test: (adding missing tests, refactoring tests; no production code change)
- chore: (updating grunt tasks etc; no production code change)

e.g.
```shell
feat: add hat wobble
^--^  ^------------^
|     |
|     +-> Summary in present tense.
|
+-------> Type: chore, docs, feat, fix, refactor, style, or test.
```

## gitignore
`.gitignore` is a text file that tells Git which files or folders to ignore in a project. It is used to avoid committing unnecessary files to the repository. For example, you might want to ignore log files, build files, or temporary files that are generated when you compile or run your application.

```shell
# in .gitignore
*.sh             # for all .sh files
.settings/       # for folder
!*.md            # md files should not be ignored
```

## git log
`git log` is a command used to display the entire commit history of the current project in reverse chronological order. Each commit is displayed with its SHA, author, date and commit message.

```shell
git log 
# my favorite git log command
git log --color --graph --pretty=format:'%Cred%h%Creset -%C(yellow)%d%Creset %s %Cgreen(%ci) %C(bold blue) <%an>%Creset' --abbrev-commit
```


### From disk to disk

```shell
git restore <changed_file>
```

### From Staging to Disk

keep the changes in disk
```shell
git reset <changed_file>
# or 
git restore --staged <changed_file>
```

discard the changes in disk
```shell
git checkout HEAD <changed_file>
```

`HEAD` denotes the latest commit in git

### From Local to Staging

```shell
git reset --soft HEAD~1
```
`HEAD~1` refers to the previous commit before the latest commit

### From Local to Disk
Keep the changes in disk
```shell
git reset HEAD~1
# or
git reset --mixed HEAD~1
```

Discard the changes in disk
```shell
git reset --hard HEAD~1
```


### Revert in main branch

```shell
git revert HEAD
git push
```


### Revert in individual feature branch
```shell
git reset --hard HEAD~1
git push -f
```

Be careful about `-f` in `git push`.  `-f` cannot be used in common remote branches on the remote

## git reset

Bring the content of the commit back to the Staging Area:

```shell
git reset [commit hash]
git reset [commit hash] --soft    #won't delete related files
git reset [commit hash] --hard    #will delete related files
```

**git reset can roll forward or backward**

### git revert

git revert is a command used to undo changes made in a commit by creating a new commit that undoes those changes.

```shell
git revert <commit id>
```

Revert merge commit:

```shell
git revert <commit id> -m 1   # Reverts the changes from the other branch
git revert <commit id> -m 2   # Reverts the changes from the current branch
```

### How to fix the conflict

#### Method 1: Merge

```shell
# update main branch
git checkout main
git pull

# merge
git checkout feature
git merge main
```

* Pros of merge: easy to use and understand
* Cons of merge: too many branches in master. Hard to read the git log and debug

#### Method 2: Rebase

```shell
# update main branch
git checkout main
git pull

# rebase
git checkout feature
git rebase main
```

* Pros of rebase: make git log clean
* Cons of rebase: hard to master. It will change the commit id of feature branches, leading to some problems

#### Best practice:

* git rebase is recommended in feature branches
* git merge is recommended in master branches

### How to delete branches

```shell
git checkout main
git branch -d foo
git push origin --delete foo
git branch --a # check whether foo is deleted or not
```

### git remote

```shell
# check the name of remote repo
git remote
​
# check the info of remote repo
git remote -v
​
# add remote repo
# origin is the default name of remote repo
# url is the github repo link
git remote add origin <url>
​
# create the branch on remote repo and push
# this command will create a new branch on remote repo
git push --set-upstream origin [Branch_name]
​
# change remote
git remote set-url origin <url>
```

### git tag
```shell
git tag -a v1.1 -m "test" 
```

### remove untracked files

Remove untracked directories in addition to untracked files:

```shell
git clean -fd
```

### git in ~/.zshrc

```shell
alias reignore='git rm -r --cached . && git add .'
alias whyignore='git check-ignore -v'
alias gg='git lg'
alias gb='git branch'
alias gco='git checkout'
alias gac="git add . && git commit"
alias gs="git status"
```

### git in ~/.gitconfig

```shell
[alias]
    lg = log --color --graph --pretty=format:'%Cred%h%Creset -%C(yellow)%d%Creset %s %Cgreen(%ci) %C(bold blue) <%an>%Creset' --abbrev-commit
```
